          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Systematic diagnostic. Step 1: check condenser coils at the back or base of the refrigerator — dust and pet hair buildup is the #1 cause of cooling loss on 800 Series units, free cleaning fix (80% of 'not cooling' calls resolve here if coils haven't been cleaned in 12+ months). Step 2: listen for the compressor — if silent and the refrigerator is warm, compressor start relay has failed (most common single component call, $95-$155 replacement, 30-minute job). Step 3: check evaporator fan behind the freezer back panel — ice buildup or motor seizure blocks airflow between freezer and refrigerator compartments, fan replacement $285-$385. Step 4: defrost system — frost buildup on evaporator coils means defrost heater, timer, or sensor failed, $245-$385 component depending on which. Step 5 (rare): refrigerant leak around compressor (oily residue signature), requires EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410) sealed-system service, $680-$1,280 depending on leak location."
